import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
import scipy.cluster.hierarchy as sch
from sklearn.cluster import AgglomerativeClustering

# Load the dataset with only necessary rows
data = pd.read_csv("C:\\Users\\nirsh\\MS23002456\\Unsupervised_Customer_Segmentation_2.csv", low_memory=False)

# Limit the dataset to the first 5,000 rows for faster processing (adjust as needed)
data = data.head(5000)

# Print the shape and columns of the dataset
print("Dataset shape:", data.shape)
print("Dataset columns:", data.columns)

# Display the first few rows of the dataset
print("\nFirst few rows of the dataset:")
print(data.head())

# Drop rows with missing values
data = data.dropna()

# Use the relevant features for clustering
features = ['qtt_order', 'total_spent']  # Adjust these feature names as per your dataset
data_sample = data[features]

# Visualize distributions of key features
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 6))
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
sns.histplot(data['qtt_order'], bins=30, kde=True)
plt.title('Distribution of Quantity of Orders')
plt.xlabel('Quantity of Orders')
plt.ylabel('Frequency')

plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
sns.histplot(data['total_spent'], bins=30, kde=True)
plt.title('Distribution of Total Spent')
plt.xlabel('Total Spent')
plt.ylabel('Frequency')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Correlation Heatmap
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
sns.heatmap(data[features].corr(), annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', fmt=".2f")
plt.title('Correlation Heatmap')
plt.show()

# Scale the features
scaler = StandardScaler()
data_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(data_sample)

# K-Means Clustering
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=5, random_state=42, n_init=10, max_iter=300)
kmeans.fit(data_scaled)
data['KMeans_Cluster'] = kmeans.labels_

# PCA for visualization
pca = PCA(n_components=2)
data_pca = pca.fit_transform(data_scaled)

# Plotting K-Means Clustering Results
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 7))
sns.scatterplot(x=data_pca[:, 0], y=data_pca[:, 1], hue=data['KMeans_Cluster'], palette='viridis', s=100, alpha=0.6)
plt.title("K-Means Clustering Results")
plt.xlabel("PCA Component 1")
plt.ylabel("PCA Component 2")
plt.legend(title='Cluster')
plt.show()

# Hierarchical Clustering Dendrogram (subsampled for efficiency)
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 7))
dendrogram = sch.dendrogram(sch.linkage(data_scaled[:1000], method='ward'))  # Use first 1000 samples
plt.title('Dendrogram for Hierarchical Clustering (Sampled)')
plt.xlabel('Samples')
plt.ylabel('Euclidean distances')
plt.show()

# Fit Hierarchical Clustering with a specific number of clusters
hierarchical = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=5)
data['Hierarchical_Cluster'] = hierarchical.fit_predict(data_scaled)

# Plotting Hierarchical Clustering Results
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 7))
sns.scatterplot(x=data_pca[:, 0], y=data_pca[:, 1], hue=data['Hierarchical_Cluster'], palette='viridis', s=100, alpha=0.6)
plt.title("Hierarchical Clustering Results")
plt.xlabel("PCA Component 1")
plt.ylabel("PCA Component 2")
plt.legend(title='Cluster')
plt.show()

# Print clustering results
print("Unique clusters in K-Means:", np.unique(data['KMeans_Cluster']))
print("Unique clusters in Hierarchical Clustering:", np.unique(data['Hierarchical_Cluster']))
